Tron: Betrayal is a two-issue mini-series published by Marvel in October 2010. It bridges the gap between the original movie Tron (Walt Disney Productions, 1982) and sequel Tron: Legacy (Walt Disney Pictures, December 2010). The series takes place in 1983 and shortly after the events of the original movie, and also features the first appearance of many new characters in Tron: Legacy.

Kevin Flynn is now in charge of Encom developing "The Grid", a digital world occupied by living programs. When the world develops a life of its own, Flynn has to seek out the help of Tron to control it.

deck:
"Peculia and the Groon Grove Vampires" is a Graphic Novel created, written and illustrated by Richard Sala, and published by Fantagraphics Books. 

It is a stand alone Graphic Novel and the only one in its volume.
description:
"Peculia and the Groon Grove Vampires" is a stand alone Graphic Novel featuring an 80-page story involving the main character Peculia. It is the only Graphic Novel in its volume. This Graphic Novel is sometimes referred to as "Evil Eye #13" but was never officially titled as such, does not have any sub-headings either inside nor out with that designation, is not a collection nor a continuation of previous stories, and was not included in that volume.

This Graphic Novel involves the adventures of Peculia, a young lady who inherits an older mansion from her deceased parents. The mansion is located at the top of a remote hill outside the non-descript town where she lives, and she has a diminutive butler who assists her with her daily routines, although it becomes apparent she needs little to no help.

Peculia goes for a walk to get some items from the local store and during her walk, she encounters a group of young women who see her. They are trying to form a "babysitter's club" of sorts, and upon seeing Peculia, decide to befriend her so she can assist with their efforts. Peculia talks to the ladies and agrees. It is also during the walk home, early in the evening after the sun has gone down where she meets yet another female. This woman talks to Peculia about a babysitting job, having learned she'd joined the group. They talk but mysteriously, the woman avoids a hawthorne tree in their path.

She is soon invited to the woman's home, along with some of the other girls from the babysitter's club and mysterious things begin to happen.
name: Peculia and the Groon Grove Vampires

description:
A reprint collection that contains the material of four comics, without covers. Collects the abruptly canceled Jack Cross series. Original planned as an ongoing series and just stopped at 4 issue, with no reason mentioned why.  Just Warren Ellis saying that there will be no more Jack Cross stories. When the reprint was slated for release Ellis would comment again on his blog "JACK CROSS was a disappointment, a project that went wrong fast and seemed to be outside my reach to fix. Gary did a yeoman job on these four issues, but there’ll never be any more." 
 
No one but Ellis and DC Comics really knows what happened and why Jack Cross only lasted four issues which we collected here in DC Comics Presents: Jack Cross.
name: DC Comics Presents Jack Cross

description:
Hate was written and illustrated by Peter Bagge it first published in 1990 and ran for 30 issues released on a quarterly schedule.

Hate is Buddy Bradley's from "The Bradley's" of Peter Bagge's Neat Stuff story. In the first 15 issues he lives in Seattle with his room mates Stinky and George, while finding love with Valerie then Lisa. Issues 16 onwards see Buddy and Lisa move back to the suburbs of New Jersey and reintroduces Buddy's family.

When asked if Buddy Bradley was an autobiographical character in an 1997 interview with Fantagraphics Peter Bagge answered "I used to tell people that he wasn’t. I mean, he is sort of a younger version of myself, but I think he’s a less well-adjusted version, as well as a more vocal, cantankerous version. One time a year or two ago a magazine asked me to answer a set of questions in Buddy’s voice. It wasn’t until I did this and realized that Buddy’s answers were exactly the same as they would have been if I answered them when I relaized that, yes, I am Buddy Bradley!"

Hate was followed by Hate Annual published in 2000.

Collected Editions

  • Buddy Does Seattle (#1-15)
name: Hate

description:
All-Negro Comics was an anthology series that focused manly on Afro-American and African heroes. It was historically important because the series was published by All-Negro Comics, which was the first publisher that had an all Afro-American publishing team. A second issue was planned and art completed, but sadly, never published. The first issue featured:

  • Dew Dillie
  • Ezekiel's Manhunt
  • Hep Chicks On Parade
  • Lil' Eggie
  • Sugarfoot
